# ── UPDATE: narr:Narrative_SynchronousReviewIntegration ─────────────────────
# Current note is minimal; memory provides rich detail about the design decision.
DELETE {
  GRAPH ?g {
    narr:Narrative_SynchronousReviewIntegration skos:note ?oldNote ;
      narr:theme ?oldTheme .
  }
}
INSERT {
  GRAPH narr:Tx_20250714T160000Z {
    narr:Narrative_SynchronousReviewIntegration
      skos:note "Design session (Scarlet + Claude, 2026-03-31 to 2026-04-02) triggered by the Tony advisory call memory as a case study. The current model: remember saves a memory, extraction runs, a PR is created, a notification goes out, and eventually someone starts a review in a separate session. The new model: remember returns with enough context and instructions that the agent immediately offers review in the same session. Three new fields added to remember's return: tx_summary (plain-language summary of what shifted), zones (domains/areas affected), review_instructions (prompt fragment for warm-start review protocol). The tx_summary is generated during extraction so it adds no latency. The handoff: saved confirmation → 2-4 bullet shift summary → zones affected → 'Review now?' with a one-line explanation. Review is strongly offered, not mandatory." ;
      narr:theme "Review moves from async PR-based flow into remember's return path, enabling immediate same-session review with tx_summary, zones, and review_instructions fields" .
  }
}
WHERE {
  GRAPH ?g {
    narr:Narrative_SynchronousReviewIntegration skos:note ?oldNote .
    OPTIONAL { narr:Narrative_SynchronousReviewIntegration narr:theme ?oldTheme . }
  }
} ;

# ── UPDATE: narr:Claim_ReviewInRememberReturn ────────────────────────────────
# Current note is brief; memory adds tx_summary/zones/review_instructions detail.
DELETE {
  GRAPH ?g {
    narr:Claim_ReviewInRememberReturn skos:note ?oldNote .
  }
}
INSERT {
  GRAPH narr:Tx_20250714T160000Z {
    narr:Claim_ReviewInRememberReturn
      skos:note "The review process moves from an async PR-based flow to a synchronous return-value flow in the remember tool. Three new fields in remember's return: tx_summary (plain-language summary of what shifted in the worldview), zones (domains/areas affected by the extraction), review_instructions (prompt fragment telling the agent the warm-start review protocol). The agent should present the shift summary, offer review, and if accepted, run the warm-start protocol. Instructions explicitly should not block future work if the user declines review. Scarlet: 'As soon as the memory returns, I want to get a little summary of here's what shifted, here's what that might affect. Do you want to start review?'" .
  }
}
WHERE {
  GRAPH ?g {
    narr:Claim_ReviewInRememberReturn skos:note ?oldNote .
  }
} ;

# ── UPDATE: narr:Claim_PromptingInReturnValues ───────────────────────────────
# Current note is brief; memory adds product-wide framing and Scarlet quote.
DELETE {
  GRAPH ?g {
    narr:Claim_PromptingInReturnValues skos:note ?oldNote .
  }
}
INSERT {
  GRAPH narr:Tx_20250714T160000Z {
    narr:Claim_PromptingInReturnValues
      skos:note "This is not just a review feature — it is a product-wide shift in how aswritten tools communicate with agents. The pattern: reinforce agent behavior at the point of tool return, not just in upfront tool descriptions and server instructions. Scarlet: 'This is part of a shift I want to start making in the product as a whole: doing more prompting in the return values from tools instead of always just up front in the tool descriptions. The tool descriptions are a good place, certainly; the server instructions are also a good place. We want to reinforce that at the actual return point by giving really clear instructions for what should happen next.' The review_instructions field in remember's return is the first implementation of this pattern. It is not a blocking initiative — the pattern will be adopted incrementally across tools." .
  }
}
WHERE {
  GRAPH ?g {
    narr:Claim_PromptingInReturnValues skos:note ?oldNote .
  }
} ;

# ── UPDATE: narr:Claim_ReviewToolAbstraction ────────────────────────────────
# Current note is brief; memory adds detail about transactions from remember's return.
DELETE {
  GRAPH ?g {
    narr:Claim_ReviewToolAbstraction skos:note ?oldNote .
  }
}
INSERT {
  GRAPH narr:Tx_20250714T160000Z {
    narr:Claim_ReviewToolAbstraction
      skos:note "The review tool currently requires a PR number. The real input is a set of transactions. PR number is one way to get them; remember's return value is another. Scarlet: 'This whole start review with PR number is really just pulling a set of transactions from that PR number. What we want to abstract here is that review should just take a set of transactions, and the PR number is an optional way to pull that set of transactions.' The review tool signature opens up: pr_number becomes optional. Transactions can be provided directly from remember's return, or pulled from a PR, or pulled from a commit." .
  }
}
WHERE {
  GRAPH ?g {
    narr:Claim_ReviewToolAbstraction skos:note ?oldNote .
  }
} ;

# ── UPDATE: narr:Claim_TierFeatureArchitecture ───────────────────────────────
# Current note is brief; memory adds the full two-axis model.
DELETE {
  GRAPH ?g {
    narr:Claim_TierFeatureArchitecture skos:note ?oldNote .
  }
}
INSERT {
  GRAPH narr:Tx_20250714T160000Z {
    narr:Claim_TierFeatureArchitecture
      skos:note "Tiers don't directly determine flow. Two independent axes do: (1) GitHub connected or not; (2) Single user or team. Scarlet: 'In the consumer AI case where this is being used from a chat context, there is no branch. There's no repo, there's no Claude code that this is being run in, and you can be switching between multiple repos while doing work. In that sense, saving to a branch is a non-intuitive operation. The case where branch starts to make sense is if you are working in a coding agent and you're actually pulling the repo, so that's GitHub only.' Feature gates: Free→Expert = save and curate your own perspective, sync review after every save. Expert→Team = multiple people contributing to the same worldview. +GitHub (any paid tier) = branches, PRs, structured cross-user review, formal consensus flow, multi-repo for Expert." .
  }
}
WHERE {
  GRAPH ?g {
    narr:Claim_TierFeatureArchitecture skos:note ?oldNote .
  }
} ;

# ── UPDATE: narr:Claim_BranchPolicyShift ────────────────────────────────────
# Current note is brief; memory adds context-dependent guidance detail.
DELETE {
  GRAPH ?g {
    narr:Claim_BranchPolicyShift skos:note ?oldNote .
  }
}
INSERT {
  GRAPH narr:Tx_20250714T160000Z {
    narr:Claim_BranchPolicyShift
      skos:note "The blanket rule 'NEVER write to main' is lifted; branch policy becomes context-dependent and prompt-guided. Branch (ref) is optional. Defaults to main. Always. Branch guidance lives in prompts (server instructions, tool descriptions) and varies by context: No GitHub: don't mention branches, main only. GitHub single user: main is default, branches available if agent context supports it. GitHub team: default to topic branch, PRs aggregate memories for teammate review. Scarlet: 'I think branch should be optional, and it should default to main. If you're in an agentic environment in which branch is a thing, there should be some part of the prompt that makes it clear that the agent should work with the user to decide which branch is appropriate.' Plan-specific tool descriptions and server instructions are needed to vary this guidance per tier — open work item." .
  }
}
WHERE {
  GRAPH ?g {
    narr:Claim_BranchPolicyShift skos:note ?oldNote .
  }
} ;

